\begin_layout Section
Statement of Motivation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is widely believed that the Turing machine is equivalent to any reasonable
 computational models.
 Yet, for centuries, the mathematical formalization of physical processes
 has been founded on the infinitely precise real or complex numbers
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ziegler2007,weihrauch2012computable,blum2012complexity"

\end_inset

 which might provide such processes more computational power.
 For example, almost every description of quantum mechanics, quantum computation
, or quantum experiments refers to entities such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\rme$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

, etc (see, e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Redhead1987-REDINA,544199,Mermin2007"

\end_inset

).
 Whether these models based on real numbers faithfully describe the nature
 or just an approximation is still an open question.
 If they are faithful, how the nature store and compute these real numbers
 to produce our experimental results would be the next natural question.
 There are at least three possibilities:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For any computable number
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Turing_1937"

\end_inset

, the nature only store the code of the Turing machine which computes the
 given number, and manipulate these codes directly during the computation
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ziegler2007,weihrauch2012computable"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The nature stores real numbers on infinitely long Turing machine tapes,
 and handle these numbers by a Turing machine
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ziegler2007,weihrauch2012computable"

\end_inset

.
 In another word, the nature stores real numbers as a whole, but compute
 them piecewisely.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The nature stores and computes real numbers as a whole
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ziegler2007,blum2012complexity"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All these possibilities are not very desirable because they suggest the
 nature might have more computational power than a Turing machine.
 On one hand, if the nature only stores computable numbers by their Turing
 machine codes, the nature might be able to decide whether two Turing machines
 output exactly the same numbers, since this is used to decide whether an
 observable is degenerated or not.
 However, testing whether two Turing machines are output-equivalent is undecidab
le by Rice's theorem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rice_1953,Ziegler2007,weihrauch2012computable"

\end_inset

, i.e., the nature has more computational power than a Turing machine.
 On the other hand, if the nature stores real numbers as a whole, any particular
 real number could serve as an oracle and give the nature more computational
 power than a Turing machine.
 For example, maybe the mass of the electron in some representation is the
 halting oracle for some representation of Turing machines.
 Then, we could solve the halting problem by just measuring the mass of
 the electron.
 This kind of possibility has been online discussed by Peter Shor and others
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PhysicsStackExchange16889"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since all possibilities that quantum theory is faithful are not very desirable,
 maybe every description of quantum theory is just an approximation.
 In this case, there is the other possibility:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The real and complex numbers only exist in our model.
 The nature is essentially discrete, and could be simulated by a Turing
 machine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have followed this approach to study quantum theory over discrete finite
 fields
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "usat,geometry2013,DQT2014"

\end_inset

.
 This yields a variant of quantum mechanics in which computationally hard
 problems like UNIQUE-SAT (which decides whether a given Boolean formula
 is unsatisfiable or has exactly one satisfying assignment
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Valiant198685,Papadimitriou1993,AroraBarak2009"

\end_inset

) can be deterministically solved in constant time.
 We then delicate analysis of the structure of the Hilbert space, the process
 of observation, and the notion of probability by teasing apart their reliance
 on the infinitely precise real numbers
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "geometry2013,DQT2014"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Proposed Question
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In contrast to our previous works that assume the current quantum theory
 is just an approximation to the discrete reality, we now assume the nature
 really use real numbers.
 However, these real numbers could not be directly accessed by human who
 is bounded by finite resources.
 Therefore, even if the nature might have more computational power than
 a Turing machine, human might not be able to acquire and use the computational
 power more than a Turing machine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to model the bounded-resource human observers, we would like the
 theories of measurement and probability replaced by a subjective probability
 model, called the interval-valued probability.
 The question is how quantum mechanics would like with the interval-valued
 probability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In particular, based on conventional probability, Gleason's theorem
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gleason1957,Redhead1987-REDINA,peres1995quantum"

\end_inset

 suggests that idea to define a state as a density matrix
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Varadarajan2008"

\end_inset

.
 Since Gleason's theorem could not directly apply on interval-valued probability
 measures, we would like to ask: How a quantum state looks like with the
 interval-valued probability? When the number and precision of the intervals
 increase, would the quantum interval-valued probability measures converge
 to the quantum probability measure induced by the Born rule
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Born1983,Mermin2007,Jaeger2007"

\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Kick-off Talk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the kick-off talk, we will begin by reviewing existing work that recasts
 classical probability spaces in a resource-aware setting and move to aim
 at recasting quantum probability and quantum measurement.
 In particular, we develop a measurement framework based on quantum interval-val
ued probability measures
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

(IVPM).
 Surprisingly, we found a quantum IVPM which can not be induced by a state,
 while Shapley proved a classical convex IVPM can always be induced by a
 classical 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shapley1971,Grabisch2016"

\end_inset

, and Gleason proved a infinitely-specified quantum probabilities measure
 can always be induced by a quantum state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gleason1957,Redhead1987-REDINA,peres1995quantum"

\end_inset

.
 Nevertheless, a quantum IVPM could still correspond to many possible states
 if it is broken into pieces.
 Our examples also suggest that a quantum IVPM could be more and more likely
 induced by a state while the intervals become sharper, i.e., the measurement
 resources increase.
\end_layout

