\begin_layout Subsubsection
Classical Probability Spaces
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The conventional definition of a probability space builds upon the field
 of real numbers.
 In more detail, a probability space consists of a 
\emph on
sample space
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, a space of 
\emph on
events
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

, and a 
\emph on
probability measure
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas$
\end_inset

 mapping events in 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

 to the real interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 We will only consider 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 sets of events and restrict our attention to non-empty finite sets 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 as the sample space.
 The space of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

 includes every possible subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

: it is the powerset
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $2^{\Omega}=\left\{ E~\middle|~E\subseteq\Omega\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 For future reference, we emphasize that events are the primary notion of
 interest and that the sample space is a convenient artifact that allows
 us to treat events as sets obeying the laws of Boolean algebra
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Boole1948,Redhead1987-REDINA,Griffiths2003"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{definition}[Probability Measure]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:ClassicalProbabilitySpace"

\end_inset

 Given the set of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

, a 
\emph on
probability measure
\emph default
 is a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas:\events\rightarrow[0,1]$
\end_inset

 such that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(\emptyset)=0$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(\Omega)=1$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for every event 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas\left(\Omega\backslash E\right)=1-\pmeas\left(E\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\backslash E$
\end_inset

 is the complement event of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for every collection 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ E_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

 of pairwise disjoint events, 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas\left(\bigcup_{i=1}^{N}E_{i}\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\pmeas(E_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{definition}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 There is some redundancy in the definition that will be useful when moving
 to quantum probability spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
