begin{example}[Two-coins experiment]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "ex1"

\end_inset

 Consider an experiment that tosses two coins.
 We have four possible outcomes that constitute the sample space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega=\{HH,HT,TH,TT\}$
\end_inset

.
 There are 16 total events including the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\{HH,HT\}$
\end_inset

 that the first coin lands heads up, the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\{HT,TH\}$
\end_inset

 that the two coins land on opposite sides, and the event 
\begin_inset Formula $\{HT,TH,TT\}$
\end_inset

 that at least one coin lands tails up.
 Here is a possible probability measure for these events: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{c@{\qquad\qquad}c}
\begin{array}{rcl}
\pmeas(\emptyset) & = & 0\\
\pmeas(\{HH\}) & = & 1/3\\
\pmeas(\{HT\}) & = & 0\\
\pmeas(\{TH\}) & = & 2/3\\
\pmeas(\{TT\}) & = & 0\\
\pmeas(\{HH,HT\}) & = & 1/3\\
\pmeas(\{HH,TH\}) & = & 1\\
\pmeas(\{HH,TT\}) & = & 1/3
\end{array} & \begin{array}{rcl}
\pmeas(\{HT,TH\}) & = & 2/3\\
\pmeas(\{HT,TT\}) & = & 0\\
\pmeas(\{TH,TT\}) & = & 2/3\\
\pmeas(\{HH,HT,TH\}) & = & 1\\
\pmeas(\{HH,HT,TT\}) & = & 1/3\\
\pmeas(\{HH,TH,TT\}) & = & 1\\
\pmeas(\{HT,TH,TT\}) & = & 2/3\\
\pmeas(\{HH,HT,TH,TT\}) & = & 1
\end{array}\end{array}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
