\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
It is useful to think that this probability measure is completely determined
 by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reality
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the two coins in question and their characteristics, in the sense that
 each pair of coins induces a measure, and each measure must correspond
 to some pair of coins.
 The measure above would be induced by two particular coins such that the
 first coin is twice as likely to land tails up than heads up and the second
 coin is double-headed.
 In a strict computational or experimental setting, one should question
 the reliance of the definition of probability space on the uncountable
 and uncomputable real interval
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Turing_1937,Ziegler2007,weihrauch2012computable"

\end_inset

.
 This interval includes numbers like 
\begin_inset Formula $0.h_{1}h_{2}h_{3}\ldots$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{i}$
\end_inset

 is 1 or 0 depending on whether Turing machine 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathit{TM}_{i}$
\end_inset

 halts or not.
 Such numbers cannot be computed.
 This interval also includes numbers like 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\pi}{4}$
\end_inset

 which can only be computed with increasingly large resources as the precision
 increases.
 Therefore, in a resource-aware computational or experimental setting, it
 is more appropriate to consider probability measures that map events to
 a set of elements computable with a fixed set of resources.
 We expand on this observation in the next section and then recall its formaliza
tion using interval-valued probability measures
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Weichselberger2000,JamisonLodwick2004"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

