\begin_layout Subsubsection
Measuring Probabilities: Buffon's Needle Problem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Measuring-Probabilities:-Buffon"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous example, we assumed the probability
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(E)$
\end_inset

 of each event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is known a priori.
 In reality, although each event is assumed to have a probability, the exact
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(E)$
\end_inset

 may not be known.
 According to the 
\emph on
frequency interpretation of probability
\emph default
 (which we will revisit when moving to the quantum case)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Venn1876,Hajek2012"

\end_inset

, to determine the probability of an event, we run 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 independent trials which gives us an approximation of the (assumed) 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 probability.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 be 1 or 0 depending on whether the event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 occurs in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

-th trial or not, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\pmeas(E)$
\end_inset

 could be approximated to given accuracy
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon>0$
\end_inset

 by the relative frequency
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{M}\sum_{i=1}^{M}x_{i}$
\end_inset

 with the probability converging to one as 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 goes to infinity, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall\epsilon>0,\lim_{M\rightarrow\infty}\pmeas\left(\left|\pmeas(E)-\frac{1}{M}\sum_{i=1}^{M}x_{i}\right|<\epsilon\right)=1\textrm{ .}
\]

\end_inset

This fact is called the law of large numbers
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Bernoulli2006,Kolmogorov1950,Uspensky1937,Shafer1976,544199"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's look at a concrete example.
 Suppose we drop a needle of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 onto a floor made of equally spaced parallel lines a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 apart, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell<h$
\end_inset

.
 It is a known fact that the probability of the needle crossing a line is
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\ell}{\pi h}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Buffon1777,DeMorgan1872,Hall1873,Uspensky1937"

\end_inset

.
 Consider an experimental setup consisting of a collection of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 identical needles of length 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 We throw the 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 needles one needle at a time, and observe the number 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{c}$
\end_inset

 of needles that cross a line, thus estimating the probability of a needle
 crossing a line to be 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{M_{c}}{M}$
\end_inset

.
 In an actual experiment with 
\begin_inset Formula $500$
\end_inset

 needles and the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\ell}{h}=0.75$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hall1873"

\end_inset

, it was found that 
\begin_inset Formula $236$
\end_inset

 crossed a line so the relative frequency is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.472$
\end_inset

 whereas the idealized mathematical probability is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.4774\ldots$
\end_inset

.
 In a larger experiment with 
\begin_inset Formula $5000$
\end_inset

 needles and the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\ell}{h}=0.8$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Uspensky1937"

\end_inset

, the relative frequency was calculated to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5064$
\end_inset

 whereas the idealized mathematical probability is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5092\ldots$
\end_inset

.
 We see that the observed probability approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\ell}{\pi h}$
\end_inset

 but only if 
\emph on
larger and larger resources
\emph default
 are expended.
 These resource considerations suggest that it is possible to replace the
 real interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

 with rational numbers up to a certain precision related to the particular
 experiment in question.
 There is clearly a connection between the number of needles and the achievable
 precision: in the hypothetical experiment with 3 needles, it is not sensible
 to retain 100 digits in the expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\ell}{\pi h}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is another more subtle assumption of unbounded computational power
 in the experiment.
 We are assuming that we can always determine with certainty whether a needle
 is crossing a line.
 But 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lines
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the the floor have thickness, their distance apart is not exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, and the needles' lengths are not all absolutely equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

.
 These perturbations make the events 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fuzzy.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Thus, in an experiment with limited resources, it is not possible to talk
 about the idealized event that exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{c}$
\end_inset

 needles cross lines as this would require the most expensive needles built
 to the most precise accuracy, laser precision for drawing lines on the
 floor, and the most powerful microscopes to determine if a needle does
 cross a line.
 Instead we might talk about the event that 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{c}-\delta$
\end_inset

