\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The mathematical framework of classical probability above assumes that there
 exists a predetermined set of events that are independent of the particular
 experiment — classical physics is non-contextual
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kochenspecker1967,Redhead1987-REDINA,peres1995quantum,Jaeger2007"

\end_inset

.
 However, even in classical situations, the structure of the event space
 is often only partially known and the precise dependence of two events
 on each other cannot, a priori, be determined with certainty.
 In the quantum framework, this partial knowledge is compounded by the fact
 that there exist non-commuting events which cannot happen simultaneously.
 To accommodate these more complex situations, conventional approaches to
 quantum probability abandon the sample space
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and reason directly about events which are generalized from plain sets
 to projection operators.
 A quantum probability space therefore consists of just two components:
 a set of events 
\begin_inset Formula $\qevents$
\end_inset

 often formalized as projection operators and a probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\qevents\rightarrow[0,1]$
\end_inset

 formalized using the Born rule
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Born1983,Mermin2007,Jaeger2007"

\end_inset

.
