\begin_layout Subsection
Quantum Interval-valued Probability Measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As argued in the previous sections, given fixed finite resources, it is
 only possible to estimate the quantum probabilities within an interval
 of confidence.
 It is therefore natural to propose the notion of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

quantum interval-valued probability measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that combines the definitions of conventional quantum probability measures
 with classical interval-probabilities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{definition}[Quantum Interval-valued Probability Measure]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:QuantumInterval-valuedProbability"

\end_inset

 Given a Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $\Hilb$
\end_inset

 with quantum events (projections)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\events$
\end_inset

, and a collection of intervals
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{I}$
\end_inset

, a 
\emph on
quantum 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{I}$
\end_inset

-interval-valued probability measure
\emph default
 is a function
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}:\events\rightarrow\mathscr{I}$
\end_inset

 such that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}(\mathbb{0})=\left[0,0\right]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}(\mathbb{1})=\left[1,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For any projection 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(\mathbb{1}-P\right)=\left[1,1\right]-\bar{\mu}\left(P\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a set of mutually orthogonal projections 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ P_{i}\right\} _{i=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{N}P_{i}\right)\subseteq\sum_{i=1}^{N}\bar{\mu}\left(P_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{definition}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
It is easy to establish that quantum interval-valued probability measures
 generalize conventional quantum probability measures.
 In particular, any quantum probability measure can be recast as an interval-val
ued measure using the three intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,0\right]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,1\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset


\emph default
, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,0\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,1\right]$
\end_inset

 are called 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
imposs
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
necess
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

as before, and 
\emph on

\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset


\emph default
 is called 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
unknown
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

because it provides no information.
 Given a quantum probability measure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\events\rightarrow\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

, we define a quantum interval-valued probability measure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}:\events\rightarrow\mathscr{I}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}(P)=\iota\left(\mu(P)\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota:\left[0,1\right]\rightarrow\mathscr{I}$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\iota(x)=\begin{cases}
\necess & \textrm{if }x=1\textrm{ ;}\\
\imposs & \textrm{if }x=0\textrm{ ;}\\
\unknown & \textrm{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

This measure represents the beliefs of an experimenter with no prior knowledge
 about the particular quantum system in question.
 Formally, we can ask: what can we deduce about the state of a quantum system
 given a quantum interval-valued probability measure, i.e., given observations
 done with finite resources.
 In the case the intervals are infinitely precise the question reduces to
 Gleason's theorem which states that the state of the quantum system is
 uniquely determined by the probability measure.
 But surely the less resources are available, the less precise the intervals,
 and the less we expect to know about the state of the system.
 To formally state and answer this question we begin with defining the 
\emph on
core
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
convexity
\emph default
 of a probability measure as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{definition}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Given a quantum interval-valued probability measure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}:\events\rightarrow\mathscr{I}$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\emph on
core
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{core}\left(\bar{\mu}\right)=\left\{ \pmeas:\events\rightarrow[0,1]~\middle|~\forall E\in\events.~\pmeas\left(E\right)\in\bar{\mu}\left(E\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is called convex if 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}\left(P_{0}\vee P_{1}\right)+\bar{\mu}\left(P_{0}P_{1}\right)\subseteq\bar{\mu}\left(P_{0}\right)+\bar{\mu}\left(P_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 for all commuting 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0},P_{1}\in\events$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{definition}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The core of an interval-valued probability measure is the set of real-valued
 infinitely-precise probability measures it approximates.
 An interval-valued probability measure is convex if whenever certain intervals
 exist then combinations of these intervals must also exist, guaranteeing
 we can add and manipulate probabilities coherently.
 In the classical world, every convex measure has a non-empty core, which
 means that the interval-valued probability measure must approximate at
 least one infinitely-precise measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{thm}[Shapley~
\backslash
cite{Shapley1971,Grabisch2016}]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:Shapley"

\end_inset

 Every (classical) convex interval-valued probability measure has a non-empty
 core.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In informal terms, this result states that although measurements done with
 limited resources and poor precision may not uniquely identify the true
 state of the system, there is always at least one system that is consistent
 with the measurements.
 Surprisingly, we discovered a counterexample to this statement in the quantum
 case, i.e., we constructed the following convex quantum interval-valued probabili
ty measure with an empty core.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}[Three-dimensional quantum three-interval-valued probability
 measure]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "ex:three-dimensional-three-value"

\end_inset

 Given a three dimensional Hilbert space with an orthonormal basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \ket{0},\ket{1},\ket{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Let
\emph on
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{I}=\left\{ \necess,\imposs,\unknown\right\} $
\end_inset


\emph default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\ps}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(\ket{0}+\ket{1})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\ps'}=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}(\ket{0}+\ket{2})$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\bar{\mu}(\mathbb{0})=\bar{\mu}(\proj{0})=\bar{\mu}(\proj{\ps})=\bar{\mu}(\proj{\ps'}) & = & \imposs\\
\bar{\mu}(\mathbb{1})=\bar{\mu}(\mathbb{1}-\proj{0})=\bar{\mu}(\mathbb{1}-\proj{\ps})=\bar{\mu}(\mathbb{1}-\proj{\ps'}) & = & \necess\\
\bar{\mu}(P) & = & \unknown\quad\textrm{otherwise}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

It is straightforward to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is a convex quantum interval-valued probability measure.
 Now assume there exists a real-valued quantum probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(P)\in\bar{\mu}(P)$
\end_inset

 for every event (projection)
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 We derive a contradiction as follows.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(P)\in\bar{\mu}(P)$
\end_inset

 then we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\proj{0})=\mu(\proj{\ps})=\mu(\proj{\ps'})=0$
\end_inset

.
 By Gleason's theorem, there is a mixed state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\rho=\sum_{j=1}^{N}q_{j}\proj{\phi_{j}}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(P\right)=\sum_{j=1}^{N}q_{j}\ip{\phi_{j}}{P\phi_{j}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{N}q_{j}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{j}>0$
\end_inset

.
 However, no pure state
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ket{\phi}$
\end_inset

 can satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $\ip{\phi}{0}=\ip{\phi}{\ps}=\ip{\phi}{\ps'}=0$
\end_inset

; a contradiction.
 
